solutions.content:
**Pre-requisite:**
*What is an Anagram?*
Two strings are said to be anagrams of each other if they are made up of the same characters with same frequency. For example: the word `LISTEN` and `SILENT` are anagrams. They are composed of the letters `E, I, L, N, S, T`.
`Insight-` The input is only `lowercase aplhabets`

**Algorithm:**
`Technique` - Group By Sorting
*SAMPLE CASE-*
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/9e9dee48-ad03-4047-8a66-b11e8dbcac7f_1628753485.5853918.png)
*SORTED SAMPLE CASE-*
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/12e377a3-1779-4e7c-ba97-f19fb5d390db_1628753533.013706.png)
* Once we have made this observation, we create a map for the same where the `key` will be the sorted string, and the `value` would be the list of all the strings that are anagrams.
* After iteration over all the strings, we get the desired group of anagrams
* The time complexity of this approach depends on the sorting technique you use to sort the strings.

**Solution:**
`In C++`
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<string>> ans ;
    vector<vector<string>> groupAnagrams(vector<string>& strs) {
        vector<string> temp = strs ;
        map<string, vector<string>> mp;
        for(int i=0; i < temp.size() ; i++)
		{
            string t = temp[i];
            sort(temp[i].begin(), temp[i].end());
            mp[temp[i]].push_back(t);
        }
        for(auto i:mp) ans.push_back(i.second);
        return ans;
    }
};
```
`In Python3`
```
class Solution:
    def groupAnagrams(self, strs: List[str]) -> List[List[str]]:
        map_dict = {}
        for i,string in enumerate(strs):
            tmp = ("").join(sorted(string))
            try:
                map_dict[tmp].append(strs[i])
            except:
                map_dict[tmp] = [strs[i]]

        return list(map_dict.values())
```
`In JAVA`
```
class Solution {
    public List<List<String>> groupAnagrams(String[] strs) {
        Map<String ,List<String>> map = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i=0;i<strs.length;i++)
        {
            char[] c = strs[i].toCharArray();
            Arrays.sort(c) ;
            String temp = String.valueOf(c);
            if(map.containsKey(temp))
            {
                List<String> list = map.get(temp);
                list.add(strs[i]);
                map.put(temp,list);
            }
            else
            { 
                List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
                list.add(strs[i]);
                map.put(temp, list);
            }            
        }
        List<List<String>> ans = new ArrayList<>();
        ans.addAll(map.values());
        return ans;
    }
}
```
**TIME COMPLEXITY - O(N*KlogK)**, where k is the length of the largest string. 
* This is because we are sorting string in every iteration.
* It would be **different for different sorting techniques** for e.g. `O(N*K) for Counting Sort`

**SPACE COMPLEXITY - O(N*K)**


**SCRAP APPROACH:**
`Brute Force-` Will give TLE on Large Testcases
* Iterate over each string in the input array.
* For each string, check with each element of the array if they are anagrams.
* If it is an anagram, add it to a group.
* Else, move the string to a different group

