solutions.content:
The idea is pretty straight forward. For any point, all points with the same slope with respect to the point are on the same line. We use CGD to avoid floating point errors.

For example, take the point (2, 2)

Take (3, 3) - the xdiff = -1, ydiff = -1, the gcd is -1: and the slope is 1 for "intercept" of 1.
Take (4, 4) - the xdiff is -2, ydiff is -2, the gcd is -2: and the slope is 1 for "intercept" of 1.
Take (-2, -2) - the xdiff = 4, ydiff = 4, the gcd is 4: and the slope is 1 for "intercept" of 1.
(Note, this is not actually in y-intercept form. The "slope" and "intercept" here are just the x_diff and y_diff divided by the gcd. So what that really means is that you must advance x by 1 when y is at 1. This is a way to define a line... lul... 

So, ((2,2), (3,3)) and ((2,2), (4,4)) and ((2,2), (-2,-2)) are on the same line...

The only corner cases are vertical or horizontal lines, which we can easily count separately for each point. (We are visiting the points in a triangular loop)

Finally, any points equal to our candidate point (2,2) we simply add to the max of the possible solutions, horizontal, vertical, or "slope buddies"

The other funny thing for C++, I noticed that you can use pairs in a map, but not in an unordered_set or unordered_map. Alternatively you could use a set of sets. 

```
class Solution {
public:

    int gcd(int pSmall, int pLarge) {
        int aRemainder = 0;
        while (pSmall != 0) {
            aRemainder = pLarge % pSmall;
            pLarge = pSmall;
            pSmall = aRemainder;
        }
        return pLarge;
    }

    int maxPoints(vector<vector<int>>& points) {

        int aResult = 0;
        int aPointCount = points.size();

        int aX1, aY1, aX2, aY2;
        int aDiffX, aDiffY, aGCD;
        int aHorCount, aVerCount, aEqualCount, aSlopeCount, aIterationCount;

        pair<int, int> aPair;

        for (int i=0;i<aPointCount;i++) {

            map<pair<int, int>, int> aLUT;

            aX1 = points[i][0];
            aY1 = points[i][1];

            aHorCount = 0;
            aVerCount = 0;
            aEqualCount = 0;
            aSlopeCount = 0;

            for (int j=i-1;j>=0;j--) {
                aX2 = points[j][0];
                aY2 = points[j][1];

                aDiffX = aX1 - aX2;
                aDiffY = aY1 - aY2;

                if (aDiffX == 0 && aDiffY == 0) {
                    aEqualCount++;
                } else if (aDiffX == 0) {
                    ++aHorCount;
                } else if (aDiffY == 0) {
                    ++aVerCount;
                } else {
                    aGCD = gcd(aDiffX, aDiffY);

                    aPair.first = aDiffX /= aGCD;
                    aPair.second = aDiffY /= aGCD;

                    aLUT[aPair]++;

                    aSlopeCount = max(aSlopeCount, aLUT[aPair]);
                }
            }

            aIterationCount = max(max(aSlopeCount, aHorCount), aVerCount) + aEqualCount + 1;
            aResult = max(aResult, aIterationCount);
        }

        return aResult;
    }
};
```

