# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- We loop all points and skip `i == j`
- calculate slope
- increment count for points that have same slope

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$ Double for loop comparing all points
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ up to N number of points as slopes
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int maxPoints(int[][] points) {
        if (points.length <= 2) { // if we have less than 2 points
            return points.length;
        }  
        int res = 0; 

        for (int i = 0; i < points.length; i++) {
            int[] p1 = points[i];
            Map<Double, Integer> map = new HashMap<>(); // <slope, count>

            for (int j = 0; j < points.length; j++) {
                int[] p2 = points[j];
                if (p2 == p1) { // skip same points
                  continue;  
                }
                double slope = 0;
                if (p2[0] == p1[0]) { // vertical line
                    slope = Double.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
                } else {
                    slope = (p2[1] - p1[1]) / (double) (p2[0] - p1[0]);
                }
                map.put(slope, map.getOrDefault(slope, 1) + 1); // must have at least 1 + other number of points
                res = Math.max(res, map.get(slope));
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

