# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
For any 3 points to be in same line, or collinear, the slope of line formed between (point 1, point 2) should be equal to slope of line formed b/w (point 2, point 3) or (point 1, point 3).

Let say there are 2 points (x1, y1), (x2, y2) respectively, then formula of slope - 

$$Slope, m = (y2 - y1) / (x2 - x1)$$

We can use this idea to maintain all the possible slopes forming from any given point, and maintain the counter for how many points lie in the respective slope.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Check if number of points given is equal to 1, if so, the answer can only be 1, hence return 1.

Visualizing before step 2 - Let say we are charting the points that we are traversing (in  a graph) and first point has already been charted. From the 2nd point onwards, we will find the slope of current point with the existing points in graph. For example, 
    For point 2, find slope with point 1.
    For point 3, find slope with point 1 and point 2, and so on.

2.  Traverse from 2nd point to last, i,

    2.1. Create a map which maintains all the slopes found and corresponding number of points in that slope.

    *Note: Here we are maintaining local set of slopes, i.e., slopes that are forming from current point only, and not universal set of slopes found throughout. Universal set of slopes will cause problems in case of parallel lines.
For example, consider points [[1,1],[2,3],[3,5],[4,1],[5,3]]. Slope b/w point 1, 2 and 3 is 2, number of points will be 3. But slope b/w point 4 and 5 is also 2 but they are not is same line. Maintaining a universal set of slopes will take counter for slope 2 to 5.
Maintaining a local set of slopes for every point allows us to consider only those points for counter that have same slope from current point.*

    2.2. Calculate slope, from current point to all existing points,
    - Calculate slope keeping in mind divisibility with 0.
    - If slope already exists in map, increase its counter, else add slope to map with counter as 1.
    - Update max points if number of points for current slope is greater.


3. Return max+1. This +1 is for the point with respect to which slopes were calculated. 


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int maxPoints(int[][] points) {
        int max = 1;

        if(points.length<=1){
            return max;
        }

        for(int i=1; i<points.length; i++){
            Map<Double, Integer> slopes = new HashMap();
            for(int j=0; j<i; j++){
                double slope = Double.MIN_VALUE;
                int denom = points[i][0] - points[j][0];
                int numer = points[i][1] - points[j][1];
                if(numer == 0){
                    slope = 0.0;
                }
                else if(denom != 0){
                    slope = numer / (double) denom ;
                }
                slopes.put(slope, slopes.getOrDefault(slope, 0) + 1);
                max = Math.max(max, slopes.get(slope));
            }
        }

        return max+1;
    }
}
```

