# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
i have used HashSet to solve the Question.
- First i have copied the array to the Sets to Remove Duplicates.
- Then i checked whether Elements of 1st Hashset is present in the 2nd Hashset or not by using .contains() Function.
- Then Add to a new Set And then copied to the integer array.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
import java.util.Set;

class Solution {
    public int[] intersection(int[] nums1, int[] nums2) {
        Set<Integer> set1 = new HashSet<>();
        for (int i : nums1) {
            set1.add(i);
        }
        Set<Integer> set2 = new HashSet<>();
        for (int i : nums2) {
            set2.add(i);
        }
        //Removed Duplicates using Hashset
        Set<Integer> Main_Set = new HashSet<>();
        for (Integer var : set1) {
            if (set2.contains(var)) {
                Main_Set.add(var);
            }
        }
        int[] arr = new int[Main_Set.size()];
        int j = 0;
        for (Integer val : Main_Set) {
            arr[j] = val.intValue();
            j++;
        }
        return arr;
    }
}
