# Hashset Solution
Using two hashsets to cross-check the common elements.
```
vector<int> intersection(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
  unordered_set<int> s1(begin(nums1), end(nums1)), s2;
  for (auto n : nums2) if (s1.count(n)) s2.insert(n);
  return vector<int>(begin(s2), end(s2));
}
```
## Complexity Analysis
Runtime: *O(n + m)*, where n and m are the vector sizes.
Memory: *O(n + m)*
# set_intersection Solution
Using a library functions for sorted sets.
```
vector<int> intersection(vector<int>& n1, vector<int>& n2, vector<int> res = {}) {
  set<int> s1(begin(n1), end(n1)), s2(begin(n2), end(n2));
  set_intersection(begin(s1), end(s1), begin(s2), end(s2), inserter(res, begin(res)));
  return res;
}
```
## Complexity Analysis
Runtime: *O((n + m) log (n + m))*, where n and m are the vector sizes.
Memory: *O(n + m)*

